## Battery Park City

A [neighborhood](/List_of_Manhattan_neighborhoods) and meticulously orchestrated [planned community](/Planned_community) residing at the southern precipice of [Manhattan](/Manhattan) in [New York City](/New_York_City), Battery Park City stands as a testament to human will—or perhaps, human hubris—in shaping its environment. This unique enclave is precisely positioned along the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River) waterfront, a shimmering, often indifferent, boundary. It finds itself geographically distinct, separated from the bustling [Financial District](/Financial_District,_Manhattan) and the more bohemian expanse of [Tribeca](/Tribeca) by the formidable barrier of the [West Side Highway](/West_Side_Highway). Directly to its south lies [The Battery](/The_Battery_(Manhattan)), a historic park formerly known simply as Battery Park, from which this constructed domain derives its rather straightforward name. Battery Park City exists on state-owned land, a bureaucratic marvel managed by the Battery Park City Authority (BPCA), itself a [New York State](/New_York_(state)) [public-benefit corporation](/New_York_state_public-benefit_corporations) established to oversee this ambitious venture.

While its primary function has evolved to be predominantly residential, Battery Park City also hosts a selection of significant office buildings. Among these are the expansive [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) complex, a financial titan, and [200 West Street](/200_West_Street), which serves as the global headquarters for the venerable [Goldman Sachs](/Goldman_Sachs). Beyond commerce, the neighborhood is home to cultural and educational institutions, including the poignant [Museum of Jewish Heritage](/Museum_of_Jewish_Heritage), the esteemed [Stuyvesant High School](/Stuyvesant_High_School), a collection of hotels offering transient comfort, and a smattering of street-level retail establishments and restaurants catering to its affluent populace. Remarkably, over one-third of Battery Park City's total area is dedicated to meticulously designed parkland and public open spaces, a planned green reprieve in the urban concrete.

The very ground upon which Battery Park City now stands is not naturally occurring; it is, in fact, a manufactured landscape. The land was meticulously created in the 1970s through an extensive process of [land reclamation](/Land_reclamation) from the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River). This monumental undertaking utilized an astonishing quantity of over 3 million cubic yards (2.3 million cubic meters) of soil and rock. This material was not merely convenient debris; it was largely excavated during the original construction of the ill-fated [World Trade Center](/World_Trade_Center_(1973-2001)), a poignant detail in the neighborhood's genesis. Additional fill came from the boring of the [New York City Water Tunnel](/New_York_City_Water_Tunnel) and other concurrent large-scale construction projects, supplemented by sand diligently dredged from [New York Harbor](/New_York_Harbor) off the shores of [Staten Island](/Staten_Island).

Battery Park City is administratively integrated into [Manhattan Community District 1](/Manhattan_Community_Board_1). For matters of public safety and law enforcement, it falls under the jurisdiction of the 1st Precinct of the [New York City Police Department](/New_York_City_Police_Department), which patrols its carefully manicured streets.

