#### Office

[Brookfield Place as seen in 2006, when it was the World Financial Center](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City))

Battery Park City, while predominantly designed as a residential enclave, also integrates a select number of significant office buildings into its urban fabric. The seven structures comprising the expansive [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) complex, along with the singular presence of [200 West Street](/200_West_Street), collectively represent the neighborhood's entire commercial office footprint, a concentrated hub of corporate activity amidst residential calm.

##### Brookfield Place complex

Main article: [Brookfield Place (New York City)](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City))

Strategically positioned at the very heart of Battery Park City and commanding breathtaking vistas of the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River), [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) stands as a formidable commercial complex. Masterfully designed by the acclaimed architect [César Pelli](/C%C3%A9sar_Pelli) and predominantly owned by the [Toronto](/Toronto)-based [Brookfield Properties](/Brookfield_Properties), this complex has long served as the prestigious corporate home for a multitude of major companies. Its roster of tenants has included financial giants such as [Merrill Lynch](/Merrill_Lynch), [RBC Capital Markets](/RBC_Capital_Markets), [Nomura Group](/Nomura_Group), [American Express](/American_Express), and [Brookfield Asset Management](/Brookfield_Asset_Management), among other prominent entities. [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) also functions as the critical [United States](/United_States) headquarters for [Brookfield Properties](/Brookfield_Properties) itself, with its corporate offices specifically located within [200 Vesey Street](/200_Vesey_Street) within the complex. [95] [96] Reflecting its significant scale and distinct identity, [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) even possesses its own dedicated [zip code](/Zip_code), 10281.

The ground floor and substantial portions of the second floor of [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) are thoughtfully occupied by a high-end mall, offering a curated selection of retail experiences. The architectural centerpiece of this retail space is a magnificent steel-and-glass atrium, widely known as the [Winter Garden](/Winter_Garden_Atrium), which serves as a grand public gathering space. Beyond the impressive confines of the [Winter Garden](/Winter_Garden_Atrium), a sizable [yacht](/Yacht) harbor, known as North Cove, gracefully extends into the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River), providing a picturesque waterfront amenity.

The complex's original developer was [Olympia and York](/Olympia_and_York) from [Toronto](/Toronto), [Ontario](/Ontario), a company that left an indelible mark on the downtown Manhattan skyline. It was formerly known as the World Financial Center, a name that clearly articulated its primary function. However, in 2014, following the completion of extensive renovations and a strategic rebranding effort, the complex was officially given its current designation as [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)). The original World Financial Center complex was meticulously constructed by [Olympia and York](/Olympia_and_York) between 1982 and 1988, a period of significant urban transformation. [6] While it sustained damage during the tragic [September 11 attacks](/September_11_terrorist_attacks), it was subsequently repaired and restored, a testament to its structural integrity and the community's resilience. The complex comprises six distinct constituent buildings: [200 Liberty Street](/200_Liberty_Street), [225 Liberty Street](/225_Liberty_Street), [200 Vesey Street](/200_Vesey_Street), [250 Vesey Street](/250_Vesey_Street), the iconic [Winter Garden Atrium](/Winter_Garden_Atrium), and [One North End Avenue](/One_North_End_Avenue) (also recognized as the [New York Mercantile Exchange](/New_York_Mercantile_Exchange) building), each contributing to the overall grandeur and functionality of the complex.

##### 200 West Street

Main article: [200 West Street](/200_West_Street)

[200 West Street, from Murray Street, looking west](/200_West_Street)

[200 West Street](/200_West_Street) stands as the imposing global headquarters of [Goldman Sachs](/Goldman_Sachs), a titan in the realm of [investment banking](/Investment_banking). This formidable 749-foot-tall (228 m), 44-story edifice is strategically positioned on the west side of [West Street](/West_Side_Highway), nestled between [Vesey](/Vesey_Street) and Murray Streets. Its location places it directly north of the [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) complex and the [Conrad Hotels](/Conrad_Hotels), across the street from the historic [Verizon Building](/Barclay-Vesey_Building), and diagonally opposite the redeveloped [World Trade Center](/World_Trade_Center_(1973-2001)) site. It holds a distinctive position within the neighborhood, being the sole office building situated in the northern section of Battery Park City, a testament to its singular presence. [97] Construction on this corporate landmark commenced in 2005, and it officially opened its doors for occupancy in 2009, rapidly asserting its dominance over the skyline. [98]

### Police and crime

Battery Park City and the broader [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) area are diligently patrolled by the 1st Precinct of the [NYPD](/New_York_City_Police_Department), with its operational base located at 16 Ericsson Place. [99] While the precinct's overall crime statistics might appear low in comparison to other [NYPD](/New_York_City_Police_Department) precincts, it's crucial to contextualize this by acknowledging that its residential population is also considerably smaller, thus influencing per-capita crime rates. In 2010, the 1st Precinct ranked 63rd safest out of 69 patrol areas in terms of per-capita crime, a statistic that, while seemingly high, must be understood within this demographic framework. [100] As of 2018, the rate of non-fatal assaults in Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) was recorded at 24 per 100,000 people. This figure indicates that the rate of [violent crimes](/Violent_crime) per capita in this area is notably less than that observed across [New York City](/New_York_City) as a whole. Furthermore, the incarceration rate, standing at 152 per 100,000 people, is also lower than the city-wide average, suggesting a comparatively lower incidence of serious criminal activity. [81]

The 1st Precinct has demonstrated a commendable trend of decreasing crime rates since the 1990s, with reported crimes across virtually all categories experiencing a substantial reduction of 86.3% between 1990 and 2018. In 2021, the 1st precinct reported a total of 2 murders, 15 rapes, 135 robberies, 121 felony assaults, 191 burglaries, 848 grand larcenies, and 68 grand larcenies auto, providing a detailed snapshot of the types and frequency of criminal incidents in the area. [101]

### Fire safety

The crucial task of fire safety within Battery Park City is expertly managed by the [New York City Fire Department](/New_York_City_Fire_Department) (FDNY). Specifically, the area is served by the dedicated Engine Co. 10/Ladder Co. 10 fire station, strategically located at 124 Liberty Street, ensuring rapid response times to any emergencies within the community. [102] [103]

### Health

As of 2018, health indicators within Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) generally present a more favorable picture compared to city-wide averages. For instance, both [preterm births](/Preterm_birth) and births to teenage mothers are considerably less common in this area. Specifically, there were 77 preterm births per 1,000 live births (in contrast to 87 per 1,000 citywide), and a remarkably low 2.2 teenage births per 1,000 live births (compared to 19.3 per 1,000 citywide). It is worth noting, however, that the teenage birth rate is derived from a relatively small sample size, which can impact its statistical robustness. [81] Furthermore, Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) exhibit a very low proportion of residents who are [uninsured](/Health_insurance_coverage_in_the_United_States). In 2018, this uninsured population was estimated to be a mere 4%, significantly less than the citywide rate of 12%, though this too was based on a small sample size. [81]

However, not all health metrics are entirely positive. The concentration of [fine particulate matter](/Particulates), which is widely recognized as the deadliest type of [air pollutant](/Air_pollution), in Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) is recorded at 0.0096 milligrams per cubic meter (9.6×10−9 oz/ft3). This figure is actually *more* than the average concentration found across [New York City](/New_York_City), an inconvenient truth for a meticulously planned community. [81] Moreover, 16% of Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) residents are reported [smokers](/Smoking), a percentage that slightly exceeds the city average of 14%, indicating a persistent public health challenge. [81] In terms of chronic health conditions, Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) boast some of the lowest rates in the city: only 4% of residents are classified as [obese](/Obesity), 3% as [diabetic](/Diabetes_mellitus), and 15% suffer from [high blood pressure](/Hypertension). These figures are strikingly lower than the citywide averages of 24%, 11%, and 28% respectively, suggesting a generally healthier adult population. [81] This positive trend extends to the younger demographic, with only 5% of children in the area being obese, again, the lowest rate in the city, compared to the citywide average of 20%. [81]

Encouragingly, a significant 96% of residents in Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) report consuming some fruits and vegetables every day, a rate higher than the city's average of 87%. In 2018, a substantial 88% of residents described their health as "good," "very good," or "excellent," surpassing the city's average of 78%. [81] However, a curious detail emerges in the retail landscape: for every [supermarket](/Supermarket) in Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan), there are 6 [bodegas](/Convenience_store), a ratio that might impact food access and choices for some residents. [81]

For residents requiring more extensive medical care, the nearest major hospital facility is [NewYork-Presbyterian Lower Manhattan Hospital](/Lower_Manhattan_Hospital), conveniently situated in the adjacent Civic Center area, providing essential healthcare services to the community. [104] [105]

### Post office and ZIP Codes

Battery Park City is administratively segmented into two distinct [ZIP Codes](/ZIP_Code), reflecting its geographical layout and development phases. The northern portion of the neighborhood, extending north of [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)), is covered by the [ZIP Code](/ZIP_Code) 10282. Conversely, the majority of the neighborhood situated to the south of [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) falls under the [ZIP Code](/ZIP_Code) 10280. [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) itself, as a significant commercial hub, is uniquely part of [ZIP Code](/ZIP_Code) 10281, while the southernmost tip of Battery Park City is encompassed by [ZIP Code](/ZIP_Code) 10004. [106] It is worth noting that the [United States Postal Service](/United_States_Postal_Service) does not operate any dedicated post offices directly within the confines of Battery Park City. Residents requiring postal services typically utilize the nearest facility, which is the prominent [Church Street Station at 90 Church Street](/90_Church_Street) in the bustling [Financial District](/Financial_District,_Manhattan). [107]

### Education

Battery Park City and the broader [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) area generally exhibit a significantly higher rate of college-educated residents compared to the rest of [New York City](/New_York_City), as evidenced by data from 2018. A vast majority of residents aged 25 and older—a striking 84%—possess a college education or higher. In stark contrast, only 4% have less than a high school education, and 12% are high school graduates or have some college education. This contrasts sharply with city-wide averages, where 64% of [Manhattan](/Manhattan) residents and 43% of city residents hold a college education or higher, underscoring the affluent and educated demographic of Battery Park City. [81] The academic performance of students in Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) has shown commendable progress; the percentage of elementary school students excelling in math increased from 61% in 2000 to an impressive 80% in 2011, while reading achievement also saw a rise from 66% to 68% during the same eleven-year period. [108]

Furthermore, Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) demonstrate a lower rate of elementary school student absenteeism than the rest of [New York City](/New_York_City). Only 6% of elementary school students in the area missed twenty or more days per [school year](/School_year), a figure significantly below the citywide average of 20%. [82] Additionally, an exceptional 96% of high school students in Battery Park City and [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan) graduate on time, far surpassing the citywide average of 75%, highlighting a strong commitment to academic success within the community. [81]

