#### Library

[The New York Public Library branch](/New_York_Public_Library)

Battery Park City proudly hosts a branch of the esteemed [New York Public Library](/New_York_Public_Library), conveniently located at 175 North End Avenue. This architectural gem was meticulously designed by the firm [1100 Architect](/1100_Architect) and completed in 2010, offering a modern and inviting space for intellectual pursuits. [116] Spanning 10,000 square feet (930 square meters) across two stories, the library is thoughtfully integrated into the street level of a [high-rise](/High-rise) residential building, making it easily accessible to the community. [116] A notable feature of its design is the incorporation of several advanced [sustainable design](/Sustainable_design) elements, which earned it the prestigious [LEED Gold certification](/Leadership_in_Energy_and_Environmental_Design), a testament to its environmental consciousness. [116]

[Sustainability](/Sustainability) was a paramount guiding principle throughout the entire design process of the library, influencing every decision from major structural elements to intricate details. This commitment is evident in the implementation of an exceptionally energy-efficient lighting system, a deliberate maximization of natural lighting to reduce reliance on artificial sources, and the thoughtful incorporation of recycled materials wherever feasible. [117] [1100 Architect](/1100_Architect), collaborating closely with Atelier Ten—an international team renowned for its expertise in [environmental design](/Environmental_design) consulting and building services engineering—engineered the library's cutting-edge energy-efficient lighting system. [118] The library's expansive [open plan](/Open_plan) layout, coupled with the generous use of glass, allows for an abundance of natural daylight to permeate the space year-round, creating a bright and welcoming atmosphere. This natural illumination is supplemented by low-energy [LED](/LED) lights that strategically illuminate communal areas, further reducing energy consumption. [119] Recycled materials are thoughtfully woven into the library's aesthetic and functional design; for instance, the carpet is crafted from repurposed truck tires, the floors are made from reclaimed window frame wood, and much of the furniture is constructed from FSC-certified plywood and recycled steel, showcasing a holistic approach to sustainability. [120] Distinctive design features include a seemingly "floating" [origami](/Origami)-style ceiling, composed of triangular panels suspended at varying angles, which adds a unique artistic dimension. Additionally, a padded reading nook is ingeniously fitted into the library's [terrazzo](/Terrazzo)-finished steel and concrete staircase, offering a cozy and inviting space for patrons. [116] The interior layout is designed for intuitive navigation, with its three distinct spatial areas—the entry area, the expansive first-floor space, and the elevated [mezzanine](/Mezzanine)—all visually unified through the cohesive design of the ceiling, creating a harmonious and user-friendly environment. [116]

The building's exceptional design and sustainable features have garnered significant recognition, including the Interior Design, Best of Year Merit Award in 2011. This was followed by The National Terrazzo and Mosaic Association, Port Morris Tile and Marble Corporation Craftsmanship Award in 2011, and the Contract, Public Space Interiors Award in 2012, collectively celebrating its innovative architecture and interior design. [116]

### Transportation

The [Metropolitan Transportation Authority](/Metropolitan_Transportation_Authority) (MTA) provides essential bus service to Battery Park City, connecting the neighborhood to the wider urban network. These services include the [M9](/M9_(New_York_City_bus)), [M20](/M20_(New_York_City_bus)), and [M22](/M22_(New_York_City_bus)) bus lines, offering convenient ground transportation options for residents and visitors. [121] In addition to the public bus network, the Downtown Alliance operates the "Downtown Connection," a complimentary bus service [122] that circulates throughout Battery Park City. This free service travels along North End Avenue and South End Avenue, providing vital connectivity within the neighborhood and linking it to key destinations such as [New York City Hall](/New_York_City_Hall), the [Staten Island Ferry](/Staten_Island_Ferry) terminal, and the historic [South Street Seaport](/South_Street_Seaport). [123]

Notably, there is currently no direct [New York City Subway](/New_York_City_Subway) access *within* Battery Park City itself, a deliberate design choice that distinguishes it from many other densely populated Manhattan neighborhoods. However, the community is well-connected to the subway system and the [PATH](/Port_Authority_Trans-Hudson) station in the adjacent [Financial District](/Financial_District,_Manhattan) via several dedicated [West Street pedestrian bridges](/West_Street_pedestrian_bridges), as well as clearly marked crosswalks across the formidable [West Street](/West_Side_Highway). Furthermore, the West Concourse, an underground tunnel originating from [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) and passing beneath [West Street](/West_Side_Highway), provides seamless indoor access from Battery Park City to the [World Trade Center](/World_Trade_Center_(PATH_station)) [PATH](/Port_Authority_Trans-Hudson) station, the [WTC Cortlandt station](/WTC_Cortlandt_station), and the extensive [Fulton Street station (New York City Subway)](/Fulton_Street_station_(New_York_City_Subway)) complex, ensuring robust transit connections.

The [Battery Park City Ferry Terminal](/Battery_Park_City_Ferry_Terminal) is strategically located at the foot of [Vesey Street](/Vesey_Street), directly opposite the [New York Mercantile Exchange](/New_York_Mercantile_Exchange) building. This terminal serves as a vital hub for ferry transportation, offering various routes to destinations across [New Jersey](/New_Jersey) via services operated by [NY Waterway](/NY_Waterway), [Seastreak](/Seastreak), and [Liberty Water Taxi](/Liberty_Water_Taxi). [124] [125] [126] Additionally, [NYC Ferry](/NYC_Ferry)'s St. George route, which connects to the [West Midtown Ferry Terminal](/West_Midtown_Ferry_Terminal) and the [St. George Terminal](/St._George_Terminal) on [Staten Island](/Staten_Island), also includes a scheduled stop at the Battery Park City Ferry Terminal, further enhancing regional connectivity. [127] [128] [129]

The West Thames Street Bridge, an integral component of the [West Street pedestrian bridges](/West_Street_pedestrian_bridges) system, which provides crucial pedestrian connectivity between Battery Park City and the [Financial District](/Financial_District,_Manhattan), was successfully completed in 2019. This modern structure replaced the older Rector Street Bridge, enhancing safety and efficiency for commuters and residents alike. [130] On June 11, 2021, the bridge was formally dedicated as the Robert F. Douglass Bridge, honoring its namesake, Robert F. Douglass, who passed away in 2016. Douglass was an early and influential advocate for [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan), serving with distinction as a senior advisor to Governor [Nelson Rockefeller](/Nelson_Rockefeller) and later as a founding member and chairman of the Downtown Alliance, as well as a dedicated board member of the [Lower Manhattan Development Corporation](/Lower_Manhattan_Development_Corporation), leaving an enduring legacy on the area's development. [131]

### Parks and open spaces

[A field in Rockefeller State Park, with the buildings along River Terrace behind it](/Nelson_A._Rockefeller_Park)
[At the corner of Vesey Street and North End Avenue is the Irish Hunger Memorial](/Irish_Hunger_Memorial)
[The Museum of Jewish Heritage from the Hudson River](/Museum_of_Jewish_Heritage)

A remarkable and defining characteristic of Battery Park City is its abundant green infrastructure: more than one-third of the entire neighborhood's area is dedicated to meticulously designed parkland, offering residents and visitors a welcome respite from the urban density. [4]

Among the significant open spaces and parks that punctuate the landscape are:

*   **[Teardrop Park](/Teardrop_Park)**: This distinctive urban oasis is nestled midblock, conveniently located near the intersection of Warren Street and River Terrace. Prior to its construction, the site was an unadorned, flat expanse. Conceived as an integral part of the neighborhood's comprehensive development plan, the park was thoughtfully designed in anticipation of four towering residential structures that would eventually flank its west and east sides. While officially a [New York City](/New_York_City) public park, its ongoing maintenance and pristine condition are meticulously overseen by the Battery Park City Parks Conservancy. The park's innovative design was specifically commissioned by the [Battery Park City Authority](/Battery_Park_City_Authority), and it officially opened its gates to the public on September 30, 2004, offering a unique blend of natural and sculpted landscapes. [132] A southern extension to this park further enhances its green footprint.

*   **[Robert F. Wagner Jr. Park](/Wagner_Park)**: This park is gracefully situated at the southern extremity of the neighborhood, directly adjacent to the historic [Battery Park](/The_Battery_(Manhattan)). From March 2023 to July 2025, the park was temporarily closed for extensive reconstruction as a vital component of the South Battery Park City Resiliency Project, an effort to fortify the area against future climate challenges. [133]

*   **[Nelson A. Rockefeller](/Nelson_A._Rockefeller) State Park**: Located at the northern end of the neighborhood, stretching along the serene [Hudson River](/Hudson_River) waterfront, this is the largest and arguably most prominent park within Battery Park City. It officially opened in 1992 and was the result of a collaborative design effort by architects Carr, [Lynch](/Kevin_A._Lynch), Hack and Sandell, in conjunction with esteemed landscape architects [Oehme Van Sweden](/Oehme,_van_Sweden_%26_Associates) and Donna Walcavage, creating a harmonious blend of urban and natural elements. [134] [135]

In addition to these major green spaces, Battery Park City offers several other significant public areas: [136] [137]

*   **Community Ballfields**: These recreational fields are strategically located along [West Street](/West_Street_(Manhattan)), nestled between Murray and Warren Streets, providing ample space for sports and outdoor activities.

*   **The Esplanade**: This expansive waterfront promenade extends gracefully along the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River), offering uninterrupted pedestrian access and scenic views from [Stuyvesant High School](/Stuyvesant_High_School) all the way to [Battery Park](/The_Battery_(Manhattan)).

*   **North Cove and [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)) Waterfront Plaza**: This vibrant area is situated directly on the river, between Liberty Street and Vesey Street, featuring both a picturesque marina and a grand public plaza. Monsignor Kowsky Plaza is located on the south side of the North Cove, adjacent to the Gateway Plaza Apartments, while Belvedere Plaza is found on the north side of the North Cove, next to the ferry terminal, offering diverse public spaces.

*   **Rector Park**: A charming 2-acre park, Rector Park forms a central green heart within Rector Place, extending gracefully on both sides of South End Avenue. It was thoughtfully designed by the landscape architecture firms Innocenti & Webel and Vollmer Associates. [138]

*   **South Cove**: This tranquil cove is located along the southern section of the Esplanade, immediately to the north of [Wagner Park](/Wagner_Park), offering a serene waterfront experience.

*   **West Thames Park**: Situated on [West Street](/West_Street_(Manhattan)) between Albany and West Thames Streets, this park provides another valuable green space for the community.

### Culture

#### Museums and memorials

Battery Park City is not merely a collection of buildings and parks; it is also a repository of memory and reflection, housing several significant memorials and museums that contribute to its cultural depth:

*   **[Irish Hunger Memorial](/Irish_Hunger_Memorial)**: This poignant memorial occupies a 0.5-acre (0.20 ha) site [8] [139] at the intersection of Vesey Street and North End Avenue. It is solemnly dedicated to raising awareness and remembrance of the devastating [Great Irish Famine](/Great_Irish_Famine) of the mid-19th century. Construction of this unique and moving tribute began in March 2001, and the memorial was completed and formally dedicated on July 16, 2002, standing as a powerful reminder of historical suffering and resilience. [140]

*   **[Museum of Jewish Heritage](/Museum_of_Jewish_Heritage)**: This vital institution serves as a living memorial to the six million individuals who were systematically murdered in the horrific [Holocaust](/Holocaust), offering educational programs and exhibitions to ensure that their stories are never forgotten. [8]

*   **[Skyscraper Museum](/Skyscraper_Museum)**: An intriguing [architecture](/Architecture) museum, the [Skyscraper Museum](/Skyscraper_Museum) is fittingly housed within [Millennium Point](/Millennium_Point), dedicated to the history and impact of high-rise buildings, a direct reflection of the urban environment it inhabits.

*   **[Hurricane Maria Memorial](/Hurricane_Maria_Memorial)**: This memorial stands as a tribute to the victims of [Hurricane Maria](/Hurricane_Maria), the catastrophic storm that struck Puerto Rico on September 20, 2017, acknowledging the profound loss and ongoing recovery efforts. [141]

*   **Mother Cabrini Memorial**: Dedicated on October 12, 2020, this memorial honors Mother Cabrini, the revered patroness of immigrants, recognizing her enduring legacy of compassion and service. [142]

*   **9/11 Memorial at South Cove**: Created and solemnly dedicated on September 9, 2015, this memorial offers a place for reflection and remembrance of the tragic events of September 11, 2001, in a quiet waterfront setting. [143]

*   **NYC Police Memorial**: Located at Liberty Street and South End Avenue, this memorial was dedicated on October 20, 1997, honoring the brave officers of the [New York City Police Department](/New_York_City_Police_Department) who made the ultimate sacrifice in the line of duty. [144]

#### Public art

[Waterfront Plaza at Brookfield Place, including fence with poetic lettering designed by Siah Armajani and granite benches designed by Scott Burton.](/Public_art_in_Battery_Park_City)

Main article: [Public art in Battery Park City](/Public_art_in_Battery_Park_City)

In the 1970s and early 1980s, before the permanent structures began to define Battery Park City, the vast, empty landfill—the very ground deposited after the [construction of the World Trade Center](/Construction_of_the_World_Trade_Center)—served as a temporary stage for various art installations. These fleeting artistic interventions included the profoundly symbolic "[Wheatfield — A Confrontation](/Wheatfield_%E2%80%94_A_Confrontation)," [145] which brought a golden field of wheat to the heart of the burgeoning financial district, and the "Art on the Beach" series, [146] [147] [148] [149] which transformed the barren waterfront into an unexpected gallery, offering a glimpse of creativity on a blank canvas.

As the neighborhood matured, public art became an intrinsic, rather than temporary, element of its design. Sculptures were thoughtfully incorporated into the parks and other open spaces, aiming to soften the urban hardscape and provide points of visual interest. Artists [Scott Burton](/Scott_Burton) and [Siah Armajani](/Siah_Armajani) played instrumental roles in the meticulous design of the North Cove waterfront plaza, a prominent public area situated directly in front of [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)). Similarly, artist [Mary Miss](/Mary_Miss) collaborated closely with architect Stanton Eckstut and landscape architect [Susan Child](/Susan_Child) on the creation of the South Cove, ensuring a harmonious integration of art and landscape. [150]

[Wagner Park](/Wagner_Park) is home to a collection of notable sculptures, enriching its public spaces. These include *Eyes*, a work by the esteemed [Louise Bourgeois](/Louise_Bourgeois); *Ape & Cat (at the Dance)*, by [Jim Dine](/Jim_Dine); and *Resonating Bodies* by [Tony Cragg](/Tony_Cragg). Within [Rockefeller Park](/Nelson_A._Rockefeller_Park), visitors can discover *The Real World* by [Tom Otterness](/Tom_Otterness); *Ulysses*, by [Ugo Attardi](/Ugo_Attardi); *Pavilion*, by [Demetri Porphyrios](/Demetri_Porphyrios); and *Sunrise, Sunset (Revolution)*, a collaborative piece by Autumn Ewalt and Dharmesh Patel, each contributing to the park's artistic tapestry. [151]

Along the scenic South Esplanade, specifically at Rector Place, one encounters *Rector Gate*, a work by R.M. Fischer, and *Sitting/Stance*, by [Richard Artschwager](/Richard_Artschwager), located at West Thames Street. From its installation in 1987 until November 2025, *The Upper Room*, a significant sculpture by Ned Smyth, was prominently situated at the western end of Albany Street, a long-standing landmark in the area. [151]

However, *The Upper Room* was regrettably removed by the [Battery Park City Authority](/Battery_Park_City_Authority) in November 2025. This decision was made to facilitate the critical installation of flood gates at the terminus of Albany Street, a necessary measure undertaken as part of the broader Northwest Battery Park City Resiliency Project, prioritizing infrastructure and safety over permanent artistic placement. [152] [153] This extensive resiliency project also mandates the temporary removal and future relocation of the distinctive granite steps and circular tables that adorn the area in front of [Brookfield Place](/Brookfield_Place_(New_York_City)). Furthermore, it necessitates the closure of the North Cove from 2026 until 2031, signaling a significant period of disruption and transformation for these beloved public spaces, all in the service of long-term climate adaptation. [154] [155]

### Notable residents

Battery Park City, with its luxurious amenities and prime waterfront location, has attracted a number of notable residents from various fields, adding a touch of celebrity to its meticulously planned environment. [156] These include:

*   [Tyra Banks](/Tyra_Banks) (born 1973), the renowned TV personality and supermodel, who once called Battery Park City home. [157]
*   [Leonardo DiCaprio](/Leonardo_DiCaprio), the acclaimed actor, is a resident of 1 Rockefeller Park, choosing this tranquil enclave for his urban dwelling.
*   [Sacha Baron Cohen](/Sacha_Baron_Cohen), the actor and comedian, was a former resident of 1 Rockefeller Park, bringing his unique brand of humor to the neighborhood.
*   [Isla Fisher](/Isla_Fisher), the talented actress, also previously resided at 1 Rockefeller Park, sharing the prestigious address with other prominent figures.
*   [Dave Gahan](/Dave_Gahan), the iconic musician, is a resident of 1 Rockefeller Park, contributing to the artistic and creative presence in the area.
*   [Kris Humphries](/Kris_Humphries), the professional basketball player, has taken up residence in Liberty Luxe, further diversifying the neighborhood's notable inhabitants.

